.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Manual"

.SH NAME
hsh \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter that reads commands from standard
input and executes them. It supports both interactive and non-interactive modes.

In
.B interactive mode,
the shell displays a prompt
.B ($)
and waits for the user to enter a command.

In
.B non-interactive mode,
the shell reads commands from a pipe or file without displaying a prompt.

.SH USAGE
.TP
.B Interactive mode:
.nf
$ ./hsh
($) ls
($) exit
$
.fi

.TP
.B Non-interactive mode:
.nf
$ echo "ls" | ./hsh
AUTHORS README.md ...
$
.fi

.SH EXECUTION
When a command is entered, the shell performs the following steps:

.IP 1. 3
Reads a line of input using
.BR getline (3).
.IP 2. 3
Parses the line into an array of tokens (command and arguments),
splitting on spaces, tabs, and newlines.
.IP 3. 3
Checks if the command is a built-in. If so, executes it internally.
.IP 4. 3
Searches each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable for an executable matching the command name.
.IP 5. 3
If found, forks a child process using
.BR fork (2)
and executes the command with
.BR execve (2).
.IP 6. 3
If not found, prints an error message to stderr and continues.

.SH BUILTINS
The following built-in commands are supported:

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell.
.br
Usage: \fBexit\fR

.TP
.B env
Print all current environment variables to standard output, one per line.
.br
Usage: \fBenv\fR

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution or exit.
.TP
.B 1
Execution failure.
.TP
.B 127
Command not found.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories in which the shell searches for
executable commands.

.SH ERRORS
If a command is not found, the shell prints an error message similar to:
.nf
\fI./hsh\fR: \fIcommand\fR: not found
.fi

If
.BR fork (2)
or
.BR execve (2)
fails, the shell prints the corresponding system error using
.BR perror (3).

.SH FILES
.TP
.B ./hsh
The shell executable.

